<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05044i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05044i">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05044i"> 44(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> stoned for picking ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> And yet they say that that was done on account of the hardness of their hearts; and that was done in a community where the law was so fierce that it <mark>stoned a man to death for picking up sticks on Sunday</mark>. Would it not have been better to stone to death every man who abused his wife and allowed them to pick up sticks on account of the hardness of their hearts? If God wanted to take those Jews from Egypt to the land of Canaan, why didn&apos;t He do it instantly? If He was going to do a miracle, why didn&apos;t He do one worth talking about? <small> R.G. Ingersoll, <a name="MOSES" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MOSES"><cite title="source">Some Mistakes of Moses</cite></a>, (1879) 14</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
